flowRoot.flowPara: > Traditionally, scientific journals own the articles and charge a fee for access. Open science is changing the way research is published giving more universal access to scientific literature..

> The practice is becoming more widespread in the scientific world, with political support for a "public money, public research" approach. The White House has declared 2023 as the Year of Open Science.
> Open Science becomes an issue during crises. The WHO, UNESCO, CERN and the OHCHR launched a joint appeal in 2020 in favour of open science during the covid crisis.
Scientific research in which the content (articles, data, etc.) is freely usable, modifiable and shareable, enabling a whole range of open and decentralised collaborative practices.

A common digital patrimony is a set of freely usable resources that can be found in different spaces. It can include any type of resource, from simple content published online to resources with a strong collaborative dynamic around them, including these « digital commons ». Questions are being raised about the discoverability and sustainability of these informational assets.

CORE is a search engine providing access to more than 250 million open access scientific documents from around 10,000 data providers. These providers range from scientific journals to open archives from universities or research centres. CORE indexes exclusively open-licensed content. This search engine is a project run by The Open University.
Link to the CORE website: https://core.ac.uk

The IPCC and IPBES, which stand for Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change and Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services, are the main bodies responsible for synthesising the state of scientific knowledge on climate and biodiversity. Their reports are freely available on their websites, with permissive copyright. A variety of people use these documents including researchers, journalists, activists and teachers to try to enlighten society about the ecological crises.

flowRoot.flowPara: An open archive is a platform for the deposit of scientific documents, a kind of digital library. Universities usually have their own open archive.
These tools will implement standards to enable specialised search engines to simultaneously explore the content of a multitude of open archives.
